@bardianne1421 the point is true only under technicality, but it doesn't actually mean anything. The system itself requires work regardless of consumption. Meaning that even if the work needed to keep the system running is met, individuals are forced to work in order to survive within it. And living within the system is essentially enforced. This is what causes "bullshit jobs." Work for the sake of work, just so people can survive. 

It's basically like if you had a bomb strapped to you that was set to detonate if you don't do as you're told. His point is that because there's no individual to trigger the detonation, the death is justified. It doesn't matter that there's no individual forcing you to work. Refusing to do so would mean you can't survive. This inherently causes problems for free market ideology. 

Hopefully that makes sense, I watched the video like two months ago

@flippydandan  I'm not even sure what you mean by "even if the work needed to keep the system running is met, individuals are still forced to work in order to survive within it". People don't work in order to "keep a system running", they work in order to survive. Just because "a system is running" doesn't mean my financial situation is secure. If you think you have enough money saved up so that you don't have to work for like a year or whatever, you can choose not to. I'm not really sure how you can say people work regardless of its impact on their financial situation (ability for consumption). Your entire first paragraph seems to allude that people in market economies are essentially forced to work regardless if they benefit from it, and i really don't see how that's the case.

Also, this bomb detonation analogy is really bizzare. If the person whose commands you have to follow isn't responsible for the bomb's existance, how is it his fault if the bomb happens to detonate in the first place. Seems to me that it's just an unfortunate situation, nothing to "justify" or not "justify" here. 

This bomb (a metaphor for the fact that by and large, we need to work to survive) is a product of scarcity, and thus wil be with us forever. Not sure how its an inherent flaw in a free market rather than just a fact of nature. Yea, if you refuse to work and just decide to sit on your ass while not having enough money saved up to live till the end of your life, you can't survive, that's how it's always been because we live in a world of scarcity. The only way to not starve in this case is to live off the produce of others. If a person or group of people voluntarily decide to support you while you do nothing, that's fine. But I'm opposed to strealing people's money without their consent in order to achieve this end.
